assumptions: Demand is known and deterministic for the planning horizon
All costs are linear and known
Transportation costs between warehouses are negligible
Parts can be stored in any warehouse regardless of type
Failed repairs become scrapped with no salvage value
Storage space requirements are uniform across all parts
All parts have same physical dimensions for storage
Perfect information about inventory levels at all times

parameters.h_r: Holding cost rate for repaired parts (20% of value)
parameters.h_n: Holding cost rate for new parts (30% of value)
parameters.p: Backlog penalty ($500 per unit per month)
parameters.c_i: Capacity of warehouse i (Best:1000, Brussels:1500, Luxembourg:2000)
parameters.d_jt: Demand for part j in period t

decision_variables.I_ijt: Inventory level of part j at warehouse i in period t
decision_variables.B_jt: Backlog level of part j in period t
decision_variables.R_jt: Quantity of part j sent for repair in period t
decision_variables.N_jt: Quantity of new part j ordered in period t

mathematical_model.objective_function: Minimize total costs = holding costs (new + repaired) + backlog penalties + warehouse rental costs
constraints: Inventory balance equations for each part, warehouse and period
Warehouse capacity constraints for each location
No backlog allowed at end of 2025
Repair flow constraints considering lead time and success rate
Total inventory across all warehouses must meet demand
Physical storage capacity limits at each warehouse
Repair capacity constraints based on success rate

python_code:
import pulp as pl

# Get data dimensions
parts = sorted(list(set(k[0] for k in demand_data.keys())))[:20]
warehouses = ['Best', 'Brussels', 'Luxembourg']
months = list(range(1, 13))

# Parameters
part_values = {i: 100 + i*10 for i in parts} # Example values
holding_cost_new = 0.3
holding_cost_rep = 0.2
backlog_penalty = 500
repair_success_rate = 0.9
repair_lead_time = 2
warehouse_capacity = {'Best': 1000, 'Brussels': 1500, 'Luxembourg': 2000}
rental_cost = 10

# Create model
model = pl.LpProblem('Philips_Optimization', pl.LpMinimize)

# Decision variables
inventory_new = pl.LpVariable.dicts("Inventory_New",
                                  [(i,w,t) for i in parts for w in warehouses for t in months],
                                  lowBound=0)
inventory_rep = pl.LpVariable.dicts("Inventory_Rep",
                                  [(i,w,t) for i in parts for w in warehouses for t in months],
                                  lowBound=0)
backlog = pl.LpVariable.dicts("Backlog",
                            [(i,t) for i in parts for t in months],
                            lowBound=0)
repair_qty = pl.LpVariable.dicts("Repair",
                               [(i,t) for i in parts for t in months],
                               lowBound=0)
new_order = pl.LpVariable.dicts("New_Order",
                              [(i,t) for i in parts for t in months],
                              lowBound=0)

# Objective function
total_holding_new = pl.lpSum([holding_cost_new * part_values[i] * inventory_new[(i,w,t)]
                             for i in parts for w in warehouses for t in months])
total_holding_rep = pl.lpSum([holding_cost_rep * part_values[i] * inventory_rep[(i,w,t)]
                             for i in parts for w in warehouses for t in months])
total_backlog = pl.lpSum([backlog_penalty * backlog[(i,t)]
                         for i in parts for t in months])
total_rental = pl.lpSum([rental_cost * (inventory_new[(i,w,t)] + inventory_rep[(i,w,t)])
                        for i in parts for w in warehouses for t in months])

model += total_holding_new + total_holding_rep + total_backlog + total_rental

# Constraints
for i in parts:
    for t in months:
        # Demand satisfaction
        period_demand = sum(demand_data.get((i,w,t), 0) for w in warehouses)
        model += (pl.lpSum([inventory_new[(i,w,t)] + inventory_rep[(i,w,t)] for w in warehouses]) + 
                 backlog[(i,t)] >= period_demand)
        
        # Repair flow
        if t > repair_lead_time:
            model += (pl.lpSum([inventory_rep[(i,w,t)] for w in warehouses]) == 
                     repair_success_rate * repair_qty[(i,t-repair_lead_time)])

        # No backlog at end
        if t == months[-1]:
            model += backlog[(i,t)] == 0

for w in warehouses:
    for t in months:
        # Warehouse capacity
        model += (pl.lpSum([inventory_new[(i,w,t)] + inventory_rep[(i,w,t)] for i in parts]) 
                 <= warehouse_capacity[w])

# Solve
model.solve()

# Results
optimization_results = {
    'status': pl.LpStatus[model.status],
    'total_cost': pl.value(model.objective) if model.status == pl.LpStatusOptimal else None,
    'inventory_new': {(i,w,t): pl.value(inventory_new[(i,w,t)])
                     for i in parts for w in warehouses for t in months},
    'inventory_rep': {(i,w,t): pl.value(inventory_rep[(i,w,t)])
                     for i in parts for w in warehouses for t in months},
    'backlog': {(i,t): pl.value(backlog[(i,t)])
                for i in parts for t in months},
    'repair_qty': {(i,t): pl.value(repair_qty[(i,t)])
                   for i in parts for t in months},
    'new_order': {(i,t): pl.value(new_order[(i,t)])
                  for i in parts for t in months}
}
